ZOMBIE AND ORPHAN PROCESSESS

Normally, when a child process is killed, the parent process is update via a SIGCHILD signal. Then the parent can do some other task or restart a new child process as needed. 
-Sometimes, the parent process is killed before the child process is killed, then, the parent of all the processes 'init' process will become parent of all the processes(PPID)

-These processes which are left by 'killed' parent processes are called as 'Orphan processes'.

-When a process is killed, a 'ps' listing may still show the process with 'Z' state. This is 'Zombie' or 'defunct process'. The process is 'dead' and never being used. These processes are different from the orphaned processes as they have completed execution and still in the process entry table.

DAEMON PROCESSES

Daemons are system-related background processes that often run with the permissions of root and services requests from other processes.

A daemon has no controlling terminal. It cannot open /dev/tty. If you do a 'ps -ef' and look at the tty ffield, all daemons will have a '?' for the 'tty'

-A daemon is the process that runs in the background desparately waiting for something to work with. For ex, a printing daemon always wait for print commands.


